Yes, Apple Finland offers refurbished products through its official online store. These refurbished items include accessories and come with a one-year warranty, free shipping, and free returns. However, Apple does not currently offer a direct monthly payment or installment plan for product purchases in Finland. Apple+2Apple Support Community+2Apple Support Community+2

Additionally, Finnish companies like Swappie specialize in refurbished iPhones and may offer their own installment plans or payment options. Swappie is a Helsinki-based startup that buys, refurbishes, and resells iPhones across Europe. Wikipedia

To integrate the images from frontmatter.thumbnail and frontmatter.images into your existing Keen Slider, you can consolidate all image sources into a single array and map over them to generate the slider slides. Here's how you can modify your code:

Updated Code Snippet 

jsx
<div class="mt-8">
  <div id="keen-slider" class="keen-slider">
    {[
      ...(frontmatter.aboutImages || []),
      ...(frontmatter.thumbnail ? [frontmatter.thumbnail] : []),
      ...(frontmatter.images || [])
    ].map((image) => (
      <div class="keen-slider__slide overflow-hidden group">
        <Image
          width={400}
          height={400}
          class="aspect-[4/3] group-hover:scale-110 transition-transform duration-500 object-cover object-center"
          src={image.url}
          alt={image.alt}
        />
      </div>
    ))}
  </div>
</div>

Explanation

  • Combining Image Sources: The code uses the spread operator (...) to merge the arrays frontmatter.aboutImages, frontmatter.images, and the frontmatter.thumbnail object (converted into an array if it exists) into a single array. This consolidated array is then mapped over to create the slider slides.

  • Conditional Checks: The use of frontmatter.aboutImages || [] and frontmatter.images || [] ensures that if these arrays are undefined, they default to empty arrays, preventing errors during the spread operation. Similarly, frontmatter.thumbnail ? [frontmatter.thumbnail] : [] checks if the thumbnail exists before including it in the array.

  • Rendering Slides: Each image in the combined array is rendered within a div with the class keen-slider__slide, which is necessary for Keen Slider to recognize and style the slides appropriately.

Additional Considerations

  • Initializing Keen Slider: Ensure that you initialize the Keen Slider after the component mounts and the images are rendered. This can be done using the useEffect hook in React or the onMount lifecycle hook in Svelte, depending on your framework.

  • Responsive Design: If you want to make the slider responsive, consider configuring the slides option in Keen Slider's initialization to adjust the number of slides per view based on the viewport width.

  • Lazy Loading: For performance optimization, especially if you have many images, you might want to implement lazy loading. Keen Slider supports lazy loading, which can be configured during initialization.

By consolidating all your images into the Keen Slider, you provide a unified and interactive experience for users to browse through the images seamlessly.

ChatGPT said:

To make your Keen Slider automatically loop (autoplay), you can add a custom plugin using setInterval to trigger .next() at regular intervals. Here's your updated <script type="module"> with autoplay logic added:

✅ Updated Script with Autoplay Loop 

html
<script type="module">
  import KeenSlider from "https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/keen-slider@6.8.6/+esm";

  const autoplay = (slider) => {
    let timeout;
    let mouseOver = false;

    function clearNextTimeout() {
      clearTimeout(timeout);
    }

    function nextTimeout() {
      clearTimeout(timeout);
      if (mouseOver) return;
      timeout = setTimeout(() => {
        slider.next();
      }, 3000); // Change slide every 3 seconds
    }

    slider.on("created", () => {
      slider.container.addEventListener("mouseover", () => {
        mouseOver = true;
        clearNextTimeout();
      });
      slider.container.addEventListener("mouseout", () => {
        mouseOver = false;
        nextTimeout();
      });
      nextTimeout();
    });

    slider.on("dragStarted", clearNextTimeout);
    slider.on("animationEnded", nextTimeout);
    slider.on("updated", nextTimeout);
  };

  const keenSlider = new KeenSlider(
    "#keen-slider",
    {
      loop: true,
      slides: {
        origin: "center",
        perView: 1,
        spacing: 16,
      },
      breakpoints: {
        "(min-width: 1024px)": {
          slides: {
            origin: "auto",
            perView: 2,
            spacing: 40,
          },
        },
      },
    },
    [autoplay]
  );

  const keenSliderPrevious = document.getElementById("keen-slider-previous");
  const keenSliderNext = document.getElementById("keen-slider-next");

  keenSliderPrevious.addEventListener("click", () => keenSlider.prev());
  keenSliderNext.addEventListener("click", () => keenSlider.next());
</script>

🔧 Notes:

  • autoplay() is a Keen Slider-compatible plugin that sets up automatic transitions.

  • It pauses on mouseover and resumes on mouseout.

  • Adjust 3000 (milliseconds) to control slide interval.

Let me know if you want it to pause on scroll, reset on interaction, or use fading instead of sliding.
